Merge all csvs into one since they all have the same columns

all_words <- bind_rows(congo_conflict, car_conflict, darfur_conflict, kenya_conflict)
non_words_to_remove <- 
  all_words %>% 
  group_by(stem) %>% 
  summarize(occurances = sum(count)) %>% 
  slice_head(n = 45) %>% 
  pull(stem)
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)
unique_stems_counted <- 
  all_words %>% 
  group_by(stem) %>% 
  summarize(occurances = sum(count)) %>% 
  filter(!stem %in% non_words_to_remove) %>% 
  arrange(desc(occurances))
## `summarise()` ungrouping output (override with `.groups` argument)

Analyze the unique stems

Median of unique terms

median(unique_stems_counted$occurances, na.rm = TRUE)
## [1] 3

Lets see the distribution of how often certain words occur

unique_stems_counted %>% 
  ggplot(aes(occurances)) +
  geom_freqpoly() +
  geom_vline(xintercept = median(unique_stems_counted$occurances, na.rm = TRUE), color = "red") +
  labs(
    title = "The distribution of word frequency",
    subtitle = "The median frequency is 3 times",
    x = "Frequency"
  )
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Because most words occur very few times, lets focus on the most repeated words instead. We define frequent words as words used at least 20 times (i.e.used in 0.6666667 % of the articles.)

unique_stems_counted %>% 
  filter(occurances > 20) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(fct_reorder(stem, occurances), occurances)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(
    x = "Words",
    x = "Frequency",
    title = "Words Used More Than 50 Times"
  )

As expected, some words are context specific and should be removed such as Nairobi, Western and Rwandan since they dont generally predict conflict. But, the rest are actually on point.
